---------------------------------------------------3.Permutations-----------------------------------------------------------------------

  ðŸ”¹ What is a Permutation?

A permutation of a set/string/array is a reordering of its elements.
For example, for ABC, permutations are:
ABC, ACB, BAC, BCA, CAB, CBA.

ðŸ”¹ Types / Patterns of Permutation Problems


1. Basic Permutations

Generate all permutations of a given string/array.

Example: "abc" â†’ [abc, acb, bac, bca, cab, cba].


import java.util.*;

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s = "AAB";
        Set<String> result = new LinkedHashSet<>(); // maintains order + removes duplicates
        permute(s.toCharArray(), 0, s.length(), result);
        System.out.println(result);
    }

    public static void permute(char[] ch, int left, int right, Set<String> result) {
        if (left == right) {
            result.add(new String(ch));
            return;
        }

        for (int i = left; i < right; i++) {
            swap(ch, left, i);
            permute(ch, left + 1, right, result);
            swap(ch, left, i);
        }
    }

    public static void swap(char[] ch, int i, int j) {
        char temp = ch[i];
        ch[i] = ch[j];
        ch[j] = temp;
    }
}




-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2. Permutations with Constraints

Apply conditions while generating:

No adjacent duplicates
Example: "aab" â†’ disallow "aab" if aa are together.

No vowels together
Example: "aeiou" â†’ arrange so vowels are not side by side.

Only increasing order subsequences
Example: [1, 2, 3] but only keep [123].

3. Permutations with Duplicates

Input may have repeating characters.

Need to generate unique permutations.

Example: "aab" â†’ [aab, aba, baa] (not duplicate aab twice).

4. K-th Permutation

Instead of generating all, directly find the k-th lexicographic permutation.

Example: For 123, 3rd permutation = 213.

5. Next Permutation

Find the next lexicographic order permutation of a sequence.

Example: 123 â†’ 132, 321 â†’ 123.

6. Permutations as Choices/Arrangements

Selecting arrangements when order matters.

Formula: nPr = n! / (n-r)!.

Example: 5P3 = 5*4*3 = 60.

7. Backtracking Permutation Problems

These follow the recursion + decision tree pattern:

Include or exclude element.

Swap elements and backtrack.

Example: classic permute(nums[]).

8. Circular Permutations

Elements arranged in a circle.

Example: For ABC, (ABC, BCA, CAB) are same in circle, so fewer unique ones.

9. Constrained Digit/Number Permutations

Digits with certain restrictions.

Example: 4-digit numbers formed using 1,2,3,4 but divisible by 2.

10. Substring/Anagram Permutations

Find all permutations that are substrings in another string.

Example: Is "abc" permutation present in "eidbaooo"? (yes â†’ "bao").

âœ… Quick Summary:

Basic â†’ all permutations

With duplicates â†’ unique ones

With constraints â†’ adjacency, order, etc.

K-th / Next permutation â†’ sequence problems

Formula based â†’ nPr

Backtracking â†’ recursion pattern

Special cases â†’ circular, digit-based, anagram
